data.content:
Yes! If you're on **MSTest v3+**, use the strongly-typed generic `DynamicData` to eliminate `object[]`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData<string, bool>(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string, bool)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

For simple inline constants like these, `[DataRow]` is even simpler:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

**When to use which:**
- **`[DataRow]`** — best for simple compile-time constants
- **`DynamicData<T1, T2>`** — best when test data is computed, shared, or uses non-constant types (e.g., objects, arrays)

Both give you compile-time type safety instead of runtime `object[]` casting.
